what i understand:

	- collect the data for breast cancer from the website( the data will contain all subtypes of breast cancer)

	- Then normalize the data cause some genes will have more depth than others(i still didn't fully understand how this works and how ill do it but this is what i understand for now)

	- and select the genes that needed for extinguishing between luminal and triple negative.

	- and analyze in which samples those genes are expressed in high level.

	- using this classify how many samples have luminal A and triple negative and which samples are luminal and triple negative and visualize using cluster plot.
	
	- normalization is just normalizing all values cause every patient sample have different depth, for my data it comes pre normalized.

	- the log 2 value is just  2 to the power of WHAT gives me this number?
	
		log2(2)    = 1      because 2^1 = 2
		log2(4)    = 2      because 2^2 = 4
		log2(8)    = 3      because 2^3 = 8
		log2(16)   = 4      because 2^4 = 16
		log2(1024) = 10     because 2^10 = 1024
		log2(1000) ≈ 9.97
	- and because log2(0) will return undefined, we need to add 1 to every expression like log2(value + 1)
	
	- p value tells if the difference we calculated can happen by chance. if low p value it is most likely to be no chance of happing randomly. high p value means the difference can happen randomly by chance. conventional p value is p < 0.05. in depth, in the gene data there will be data from many patients from different age group tumor size and stuff, this difference is purely random every human differ but we don't need this gene, we need the genes that actually separate luminal A from triple negative. so we find average for every gene expression if difference of random gene is lower its not significant, it doesn't not affect the classification so we ignore that, but if the difference is high we use it as a classifying method.
	
	- for finding adjusted p value we rank the genes by their normal p value from smallest to largest then use this formula:

	adjusted p value: raw p value x (total number of genes / ranking of the gene)



